1
00:00:52,886 --> 00:00:55,252
<i>Ah, there it is. My house.</i>

2
00:00:56,156 --> 00:00:59,557
<i>And good old Cleveland Street.</i>
<i>How could I ever forget it?</i>

3
00:01:00,226 --> 00:01:03,127
<i>And there I am,</i>
<i>with that dumb round face and...</i>

4
00:01:03,196 --> 00:01:05,027
<i>that stupid stocking cap.</i>

5
00:01:05,865 --> 00:01:08,834
<i>But no matter. Christmas was on its way.</i>

6
00:01:09,135 --> 00:01:11,933
<i>Lovely, glorious, beautiful Christmas...</i>

7
00:01:12,272 --> 00:01:14,866
<i>around which the entire kid year revolved.</i>

8
00:01:38,698 --> 00:01:42,498
<i>Downtown Hohman was prepared</i>
<i>for its yearly bacchanalia of...</i>

9
00:01:42,635 --> 00:01:45,229
<i>peace on earth and good will to men.</i>

10
00:02:35,188 --> 00:02:38,885
<i>Higbees' corner window</i>
<i>was traditionally a high-water mark...</i>

11
00:02:38,958 --> 00:02:40,949
<i>of the pre-Christmas season.</i>

12
00:02:42,228 --> 00:02:46,528
<i>First nighters, packed earmuff to earmuff,</i>
<i>jostled in wonderment...</i>

13
00:02:47,066 --> 00:02:50,433
<i>before a golden tinkling display...</i>

14
00:02:50,770 --> 00:02:53,898
<i>of mechanized, electronic joy.</i>

15
00:03:38,484 --> 00:03:40,281
<i>Wow, there it is.</i>

16
00:03:41,354 --> 00:03:43,788
<i>The holy grail of Christmas gifts.</i>

17
00:03:43,856 --> 00:03:46,757
<i>The Red Ryder 200-shot range model...</i>

18
00:03:46,826 --> 00:03:47,986
<i>air rifle.</i>

19
00:03:48,895 --> 00:03:50,863
<i>And there he is.</i>

20
00:03:51,364 --> 00:03:52,854
<i>Red Ryder himself.</i>

21
00:03:53,299 --> 00:03:57,599
<i>In his hand was the knurled stock</i>
<i>of as coolly deadly-looking...</i>

22
00:03:57,670 --> 00:04:01,663
<i>a piece of weaponry</i>
<i>as ever I had laid eyes on.</i>

23
00:04:06,379 --> 00:04:10,372
<i>For weeks, I had been scheming</i>
<i>to get my mitts on one of these...</i>

24
00:04:10,483 --> 00:04:13,179
<i>fearsome blue-steel beauties.</i>

25
00:04:13,386 --> 00:04:17,618
<i>My fevered brain seethed</i>
<i>with the effort of trying to come up with...</i>

26
00:04:17,690 --> 00:04:21,558
<i>the infinitely subtle devices</i>
<i>necessary to implant...</i>

27
00:04:21,628 --> 00:04:24,825
<i>the Red Ryder range model</i>
<i>air rifle indelibly...</i>

28
00:04:25,131 --> 00:04:27,497
<i>into my parents' subconscious.</i>

29
00:04:27,767 --> 00:04:28,734
Ralphie!

30
00:04:29,269 --> 00:04:30,236
Randy!

31
00:04:30,403 --> 00:04:32,234
Down here in two minutes!

32
00:04:32,639 --> 00:04:34,607
And I mean two minutes!

33
00:04:34,674 --> 00:04:37,142
Come on, Ralphie. I got here first!

34
00:04:43,416 --> 00:04:44,781
Cut it out.

35
00:05:10,543 --> 00:05:13,774
<i>My mother, grabbing for her copy</i>
<i>of</i> Look <i>magazine...</i>

36
00:05:14,180 --> 00:05:18,480
<i>would find herself cleverly trapped</i>
<i>into reading a Red Ryder sales pitch.</i>

37
00:05:21,321 --> 00:05:23,721
They traded Bullfrog. I don't believe it.

38
00:05:24,357 --> 00:05:25,517
What's that?

39
00:05:26,025 --> 00:05:28,823
Well, for Christ's sake,
the Sox traded Bullfrog...

40
00:05:28,895 --> 00:05:31,022
the only player they've got,
for Shottenhoffer.

41
00:05:31,164 --> 00:05:33,724
'<i>'</i>Four Eyes'<i>'</i> Shottenhoffer,
a utility infielder.

42
00:05:33,966 --> 00:05:36,958
Got a whole goddamned team
of utility infielders.

43
00:05:37,036 --> 00:05:38,435
That's nice.

44
00:05:38,604 --> 00:05:40,504
Ralphie, on the double!

45
00:05:42,141 --> 00:05:44,371
Did you hear about this guy
who swallowed a yo-yo?

46
00:05:44,477 --> 00:05:47,139
- Swallowed a yo-yo?
- On a bet.

47
00:05:47,213 --> 00:05:49,738
Some clodhopper down in Griffith, Indiana.

48
00:05:51,084 --> 00:05:53,814
They write the silliest things
in the newspapers.

49
00:05:54,220 --> 00:05:56,848
What do you mean, silly?
I mean that's real news.

50
00:05:56,956 --> 00:05:59,049
That's not like that politics slop.

51
00:06:00,159 --> 00:06:04,823
What is the name
of the Lone Ranger's nephew's horse?

52
00:06:05,531 --> 00:06:07,328
Victor. His name is Victor.

53
00:06:07,734 --> 00:06:10,726
- How the hell did you know that?
- Everybody knows that.

54
00:06:12,405 --> 00:06:15,033
That's another one of your silly puzzles?

55
00:06:15,241 --> 00:06:17,573
Yeah, it's another one of our silly puzzles.

56
00:06:17,643 --> 00:06:21,010
Could be worth $50,000.

57
00:06:22,148 --> 00:06:23,911
What kind is it this time?

58
00:06:24,350 --> 00:06:27,478
Name the great characters
in American literature.

59
00:06:28,254 --> 00:06:31,712
Victor?
The Lone Ranger's nephew's horse?

60
00:06:31,958 --> 00:06:35,223
<i>Meanwhile, I struggled</i>
<i>for exactly the right BB gun hint.</i>

61
00:06:35,294 --> 00:06:36,727
<i>It had to be firm, but subtle.</i>

62
00:06:36,963 --> 00:06:39,989
Flick says he saw some grizzly bears
near Pulaski's candy store.

63
00:06:45,905 --> 00:06:49,739
<i>They looked at me as if</i>
<i>I had lobsters crawling out of my ears.</i>

64
00:06:50,810 --> 00:06:54,576
<i>I could tell that I was in imminent danger</i>
<i>of over-playing my hand.</i>

65
00:06:55,415 --> 00:06:57,315
<i>Casually, I switched tactics.</i>

66
00:06:57,984 --> 00:06:59,076
Hey, Dad!

67
00:07:00,386 --> 00:07:03,651
I'll bet you'll never guess
what I got you for Christmas.

68
00:07:05,191 --> 00:07:06,522
A new furnace.

69
00:07:08,361 --> 00:07:09,919
That's a good one, Dad.

70
00:07:11,330 --> 00:07:14,561
<i>My old man was one</i>
<i>of the most feared furnace-fighters...</i>

71
00:07:14,634 --> 00:07:16,397
<i>in northern Indiana.</i>

72
00:07:16,769 --> 00:07:19,499
Hurry up,
you're going to be late for school.

73
00:07:19,806 --> 00:07:22,172
Yeah. I'm running late already.

74
00:07:22,442 --> 00:07:23,966
<i>Round one was over.</i>

75
00:07:24,844 --> 00:07:25,970
<i>Parents, one.</i>

76
00:07:26,112 --> 00:07:27,170
<i>Kids, zip.</i>

77
00:07:28,714 --> 00:07:31,581
<i>I could feel the Christmas noose</i>
<i>beginning to tighten.</i>

78
00:07:31,918 --> 00:07:34,887
<i>Maybe what happened next</i>
<i>was inevitable.</i>

79
00:07:34,954 --> 00:07:37,548
Ralphie, what would you like
for Christmas?

80
00:07:37,690 --> 00:07:39,885
<i>Horrified, I heard myself blurt it out.</i>

81
00:07:39,992 --> 00:07:44,019
I want an official Red Ryder carbine action
200-shot range model air rifle.

82
00:07:45,264 --> 00:07:47,198
No. Shoot your eye out.

83
00:07:47,266 --> 00:07:51,032
<i>Oh, no! It was</i>
<i>the classic mother-BB gun block.</i>

84
00:07:51,471 --> 00:07:52,995
<i>"You'll shoot your eye out."</i>

85
00:07:53,239 --> 00:07:56,868
<i>That deadly phrase uttered</i>
<i>many times before by hundreds...</i>

86
00:07:56,976 --> 00:07:58,944
<i>of mothers was not surmountable...</i>

87
00:07:59,011 --> 00:08:01,036
<i>by any means known to kid-dom.</i>

88
00:08:01,214 --> 00:08:05,014
<i>But such was my mania,</i>
<i>my desire for a Red Ryder carbine...</i>

89
00:08:05,117 --> 00:08:08,382
<i>that I immediately began</i>
<i>to rebuild the dike.</i>

90
00:08:09,489 --> 00:08:12,583
I was just kidding.
Even though Flick is getting one.

91
00:08:13,259 --> 00:08:14,692
I'd just like some Tinkertoys.

92
00:08:14,760 --> 00:08:17,320
<i>I couldn't believe my own ears.</i>
<i>Tinkertoys?</i>

93
00:08:17,463 --> 00:08:18,862
<i>She'd never buy it.</i>

94
00:08:19,298 --> 00:08:21,129
BB guns are dangerous.

95
00:08:21,200 --> 00:08:22,792
I don't want anyone shooting his eye out.

96
00:08:28,674 --> 00:08:32,508
Randy, will you eat?
There are starving people in China.

97
00:08:41,954 --> 00:08:44,616
<i>Mothers know nothing</i>
<i>about creeping marauders...</i>

98
00:08:44,790 --> 00:08:46,781
<i>burrowing through the snow</i>
<i>toward the kitchen...</i>

99
00:08:46,859 --> 00:08:50,386
<i>where only you, and you alone,</i>
<i>stand between your tiny...</i>

100
00:08:50,563 --> 00:08:53,293
<i>huddled family and insensate evil.</i>

101
00:09:01,173 --> 00:09:04,404
Save us, Ralphie!
I just knew those bad guys...

102
00:09:04,477 --> 00:09:06,911
would be coming for us in the end!

103
00:09:07,813 --> 00:09:11,044
Don't worry, Dad.
As long as I got OI' Blue<i>...</i>

104
00:09:15,721 --> 00:09:17,154
What've we got here, folks?

105
00:09:17,223 --> 00:09:20,158
Well, we figure it's Black Bart, Ralph.

106
00:09:20,526 --> 00:09:22,790
Well, just me and my trusty old...

107
00:09:22,895 --> 00:09:26,592
Red Ryder carbine-action
200-shot range model air rifle.

108
00:09:27,099 --> 00:09:29,659
Lucky I've got a compass in the stock.

109
00:09:29,902 --> 00:09:32,132
Well, I think I better have a look here.

110
00:09:46,085 --> 00:09:47,245
Oh, no!

111
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:50,018
It's OI' Blue!

112
00:09:50,323 --> 00:09:51,722
Oh, no!

113
00:09:52,525 --> 00:09:54,117
Cheese it, boys!

114
00:10:06,205 --> 00:10:09,902
There's another one!
He's a dead-eye, ain't he?

115
00:10:17,116 --> 00:10:18,674
Okay, Ralphie!

116
00:10:18,751 --> 00:10:21,845
You win this time, but we'll be back!

117
00:10:26,859 --> 00:10:28,258
<i>Adiós</i>, Bart.

118
00:10:28,961 --> 00:10:32,624
But if you do come back,
you'll be pushing up daisies!

119
00:10:37,570 --> 00:10:39,037
And don't you forget it!

120
00:10:39,105 --> 00:10:40,663
<i>Well, son, you saved us!</i>

121
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:43,766
<i>We were goners for sure!</i>
<i>And you saved us!</i>

122
00:10:52,251 --> 00:10:53,616
Oldsmobile!

123
00:10:54,020 --> 00:10:55,544
A pile of junk!

124
00:10:56,789 --> 00:10:58,984
That goddamned Olds is froze up again!

125
00:10:59,058 --> 00:11:03,859
<i>Some men are Baptists, others Catholics.</i>
<i>My father was an Oldsmobile man.</i>

126
00:11:04,163 --> 00:11:08,224
That son of a bitch would freeze up
in the middle of summer on the Equator!

127
00:11:08,601 --> 00:11:11,263
- Little pitchers<i>...</i>
- Hold it!

128
00:11:24,650 --> 00:11:26,174
It's a clinker!

129
00:11:27,987 --> 00:11:30,114
That blasted, stupid furnace.

130
00:11:30,189 --> 00:11:31,520
Dadgummit!

131
00:11:36,762 --> 00:11:38,252
Damn skates!

132
00:11:41,167 --> 00:11:43,362
For Christ's sake,
open up the damper, will you?

133
00:11:43,436 --> 00:11:46,132
Who the hell turned it
all the way down again?

134
00:11:47,106 --> 00:11:48,130
Blasted!

135
00:11:57,783 --> 00:12:02,516
<i>In the heat of battle,</i>
<i>my father wove a tapestry of obscenity...</i>

136
00:12:02,755 --> 00:12:07,124
<i>that as far as we know is still hanging</i>
<i>in space over Lake Michigan.</i>

137
00:12:18,537 --> 00:12:20,937
<i>Preparing to go to school</i>
<i>was like getting ready...</i>

138
00:12:21,006 --> 00:12:23,474
<i>for extended deep-sea diving.</i>

139
00:12:42,962 --> 00:12:46,864
- Come on, Mom, we're going to be late!
- Just wait, Ralph!

140
00:12:48,100 --> 00:12:50,660
<i>My kid brother looked like</i>
<i>a tick about to pop.</i>

141
00:12:50,736 --> 00:12:51,532
What?

142
00:12:52,738 --> 00:12:53,568
What is it?

143
00:12:54,540 --> 00:12:56,201
What is it?

144
00:13:00,179 --> 00:13:03,478
- What is it?
- I can't put my arms down!

145
00:13:15,060 --> 00:13:17,620
Well, put your arms down
when you get to school.

146
00:13:47,593 --> 00:13:49,083
Hey, Flick! Wait up.

147
00:13:49,228 --> 00:13:50,456
Wait up!

148
00:13:51,163 --> 00:13:52,221
So what are you doing?

149
00:13:52,464 --> 00:13:54,898
What does it look like I'm doing?
Picking goobers?

150
00:13:55,134 --> 00:13:58,535
Hey, listen, smart ass.
I asked my old man about sticking...

151
00:13:58,604 --> 00:14:01,004
your tongue to metal light poles
in winter...

152
00:14:01,073 --> 00:14:04,474
and he says it will freeze right to the pole
just like I told you.

153
00:14:04,710 --> 00:14:05,734
Baloney.

154
00:14:05,811 --> 00:14:07,779
What would your old man know
about anything?

155
00:14:07,847 --> 00:14:10,145
He knows because he once saw a guy
stick his tongue...

156
00:14:10,216 --> 00:14:13,811
to a railroad track on a bet
and the fire department had to come...

157
00:14:13,886 --> 00:14:17,754
to get the guy's tongue off the track
because he couldn't get it off.

158
00:14:17,823 --> 00:14:19,586
Come on, guys, wait up!

159
00:14:19,658 --> 00:14:21,148
Come on, guys!

160
00:14:21,627 --> 00:14:23,857
Come on, guys, wait up!

161
00:14:29,101 --> 00:14:30,500
I can't get up!

162
00:14:31,804 --> 00:14:33,567
I can't get up!

163
00:14:33,639 --> 00:14:34,571
Help!

164
00:14:36,008 --> 00:14:38,272
I can't get out! Help me!

165
00:14:39,678 --> 00:14:41,339
Come on, Flick, wait up for me.

166
00:14:41,447 --> 00:14:43,244
I can't get up!

167
00:14:46,719 --> 00:14:47,515
Come on.

168
00:14:47,586 --> 00:14:49,918
Get up. Sit up. Come on.

169
00:14:51,757 --> 00:14:53,190
You're okay. Come on, let's go.

170
00:14:53,259 --> 00:14:54,590
Come on, you're all right!

171
00:15:03,836 --> 00:15:04,803
Miss Shields!

172
00:15:05,804 --> 00:15:06,862
All right, everyone...

173
00:15:06,939 --> 00:15:08,600
take your seats, please.

174
00:15:16,649 --> 00:15:18,446
Good morning, class.

175
00:15:18,517 --> 00:15:21,850
Good morning, Miss Shields.

176
00:15:56,689 --> 00:15:59,089
Open your books to Page 32.

177
00:15:59,158 --> 00:16:02,025
And as you'll remember, Silas Marner<i>...</i>

178
00:16:12,504 --> 00:16:15,132
You're full of beans and so's your old man.

179
00:16:16,308 --> 00:16:18,538
- Says who?
- Says me.

180
00:16:18,610 --> 00:16:20,510
Well, I double-dare you.

181
00:16:20,579 --> 00:16:23,173
<i>The exact exchange and nuance...</i>

182
00:16:23,315 --> 00:16:26,773
<i>of phrase in this ritual is very important.</i>

183
00:16:27,019 --> 00:16:29,579
Are you kidding?
Stick my tongue to that stupid pole?

184
00:16:29,688 --> 00:16:30,655
That's dumb.

185
00:16:30,723 --> 00:16:32,691
That's 'cause you know it will stick!

186
00:16:32,791 --> 00:16:34,383
You're full of it.

187
00:16:34,927 --> 00:16:37,054
Well, I double dog-dare you!

188
00:16:37,596 --> 00:16:40,827
<i>Now it was serious. A double dog-dare.</i>

189
00:16:41,333 --> 00:16:43,494
<i>What else was left but a "triple-dare you"?</i>

190
00:16:43,602 --> 00:16:46,127
<i>And finally,</i>
<i>the coup de grâce of all dares...</i>

191
00:16:46,205 --> 00:16:48,605
<i>the sinister triple dog-dare!</i>

192
00:16:49,208 --> 00:16:51,768
I triple dog-dare you!

193
00:16:52,778 --> 00:16:55,246
<i>Schwartz created</i>
<i>a slight breach of etiquette...</i>

194
00:16:55,347 --> 00:16:58,976
<i>by skipping the triple-dare</i>
<i>and going right for the throat.</i>

195
00:16:59,051 --> 00:17:00,382
All right, all right.

196
00:17:10,095 --> 00:17:13,428
- Go on, smart ass, and do it!
- I'm going!

197
00:17:14,099 --> 00:17:18,160
<i>Flick's spine stiffened,</i>
<i>his lips curled in a defiant sneer.</i>

198
00:17:18,704 --> 00:17:20,672
<i>There was no going back now.</i>

199
00:17:23,709 --> 00:17:25,301
This is nothing.

200
00:17:29,681 --> 00:17:31,308
Stuck? Stuck!

201
00:17:31,383 --> 00:17:33,476
Stuck! Stuck!

202
00:17:39,391 --> 00:17:40,483
Jeez!

203
00:17:40,626 --> 00:17:42,059
It really works!

204
00:17:42,127 --> 00:17:43,560
Look at him!

205
00:17:53,906 --> 00:17:55,305
Ralphie, come back!

206
00:17:55,374 --> 00:17:58,775
- Come back! Don't leave me! Come back!
- But the bell rang!

207
00:17:58,911 --> 00:18:02,403
- What are we going to do?
- I don't know! The bell rang!

208
00:18:12,591 --> 00:18:13,853
Where's Flick?

209
00:18:15,594 --> 00:18:16,925
Has anyone seen Flick?

210
00:18:17,096 --> 00:18:18,825
<i>Flick? Flick who?</i>

211
00:18:18,897 --> 00:18:21,024
He was at recess, wasn't he?

212
00:18:22,668 --> 00:18:25,159
Ralphie, do you know where Flick is?

213
00:18:30,809 --> 00:18:34,210
I said has anyone seen Flick?

214
00:18:36,582 --> 00:18:38,209
Yes, Esther Jane?

215
00:18:44,289 --> 00:18:45,881
Oh, my God!

216
00:19:06,745 --> 00:19:09,236
Holy cow, it's the fire department!

217
00:19:16,355 --> 00:19:18,084
Wow, it's the cops!

218
00:20:10,576 --> 00:20:14,603
Now, I know that some of you
put Flick up to this.

219
00:20:17,316 --> 00:20:19,876
But, he has refused to say who.

220
00:20:22,487 --> 00:20:25,115
But those who did it know their blame.

221
00:20:27,259 --> 00:20:30,319
And I'm sure the guilt you feel...

222
00:20:30,562 --> 00:20:34,521
is far worse than any punishment
you might receive.

223
00:20:38,837 --> 00:20:40,964
Now, don't you feel terrible?

224
00:20:42,074 --> 00:20:44,907
Don't you feel remorse
for what you have done?

225
00:20:47,312 --> 00:20:50,076
That's all I'm going to say
about poor Flick.

226
00:20:53,118 --> 00:20:56,576
<i>Adults love to say things like that.</i>
<i>But kids know better.</i>

227
00:20:56,655 --> 00:21:00,489
<i>We knew darn well</i>
<i>it was always better not to get caught.</i>

228
00:21:00,592 --> 00:21:03,857
Now, boys and girls,
I'm going to give you an assignment.

229
00:21:05,063 --> 00:21:06,758
I want you to write...

230
